  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Expositor's Greek Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 8:59",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". What the Jews thought of the assertion appeared in their action: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἦραν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " … ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "αὐτόν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Believing that He was speaking sheer blasphemy and claiming equality with the great “I Am,” they sought to stone Him. For this purpose there was material ready to hand even in the Temple court, for, as Lightfoot reminds us, the building was still going on. “A stoning in the temple is mentioned by Josephus, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Ant.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", xvii. 9, 3,” Meyer.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Ἰησοῦς δὲ ἐκρύβη καὶ ἐξῆλθεν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". “But Jesus went out unperceived”; on this usage ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "vide",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Winer, and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "cf.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Thayer. Why it should be supposed that there is anything miraculous or doketic in this (Holtzmann and others) does not appear. Many in the crowd would favour the escape of Jesus. The remaining words of the chapter are omitted by recent editors.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "59",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Then took they up stones",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Or, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Therefore",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "took they up stones",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", i.e. in consequence of His last words. They see clearly what He means. He has taken to Himself the Divine Name and they prepare to stone Him for blasphemy. Material lying there for completing and repairing the Temple would supply them with missiles. Comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 10:31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 10:33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "but Jesus hid himself",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Probably we are not to understand a miraculous withdrawal as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 4:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where the ‘passing through the midst of them’ seems to be miraculous. Here we need not suppose more than that He drew back into the crowd away from those who had taken up stones. The Providence which ordered that as yet the fears of the hierarchy should prevail over their hostility (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 7:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 8:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), ruled that the less hostile in this multitude should screen Him from the fury of the more fanatical. It is quite arbitrary to invert the clauses and render, ‘Jesus went out of the Temple and hid Himself.’",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "going through the midst of them, and so passed by",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] These words are apparently an insertion, and probably an adaptation of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 4:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". No English Version previous to the one of 1611 contains the passage.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "As a comment on the whole discourse see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Peter 2:22-23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", remembering that S. Peter was very possibly present on the occasion.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "“The whole of the Jews’ reasoning is strictly what we should expect from them. These constant appeals to their descent from Abraham, these repeated imputations of diabolic possession, this narrow intelligence bounded by the letter, this jealousy of anything that seemed in the slightest degree to trench on their own rigid monotheism—all these, down to the touch in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 8:57",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", in which the age they fix upon in round numbers is that assigned to completed manhood, give local truth and accuracy to the picture; which in any case, we may say confidently, must have been drawn by a Palestinian Jew, and was in all probability drawn by a Jew who had been himself an early disciple of Christ.” S. p. 160.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
